{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641415"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:26:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:26:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17878"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17878"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78733"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10592"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64077"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"10078"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24695"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78733"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAmino acids serve multiple metabolic functions beyond protein synthesis in human cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following molecules can be directly synthesised from amino acids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipids","Nucleotides","Vitamins","Carbohydrates","Minerals"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Enucleotides\u003C/strong\u003E. Amino acids provide the nitrogenous bases necessary for nucleotide synthesis. Specifically, amino acids like glutamine, aspartate and glycine are direct precursors in the biosynthetic pathways for both purine and pyrimidine nucleotides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipids\u003C/strong\u003E are synthesised primarily from fatty acids and glycerol. While amino acids can be converted to acetyl-CoA (a precursor for fatty acid synthesis), they are not direct precursors for lipids.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamins\u003C/strong\u003E are essential organic compounds that must be obtained from dietary sources as humans cannot synthesise them from amino acids.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbohydrates\u003C/strong\u003E are synthesised primarily from glucose and other monosaccharides. Although amino acids can undergo gluconeogenesis to form glucose, this is not a direct synthetic pathway.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinerals\u003C/strong\u003E are inorganic elements that cannot be synthesised from any organic compounds including amino acids. They must be obtained from dietary sources.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the metabolic fates of amino acids is crucial as they serve as building blocks not only for proteins but also for important molecules like nucleotides which are essential for DNA and RNA synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Amino acids are essential precursors for nucleotide synthesis, particularly the nitrogenous bases of DNA and RNA.","Specific amino acids like glutamine, aspartate and glycine directly contribute to nucleotide synthesis.","While amino acids can be converted to intermediates like acetyl-CoA, they are not direct precursors for lipids, vitamins, carbohydrates or minerals."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Amino Acid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Apr 1;13(4):a040584. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040584. PMID: 33795250; PMCID: PMC8015690.","Ling ZN, Jiang YF, Ru JN, Lu JH, Ding B, Wu J. Amino acid metabolism in health and disease. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2023 Sep 13;8(1):345. doi: 10.1038/s41392-023-01569-3. PMID: 37699892; PMCID: PMC10497558."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17878"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64077"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T15:52:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T15:54:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10592"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78733"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i